interfaces.label: AnomaliesTableRecord
description: Anomaly table record, representing the fields shown in the ML UI anomalies table.

children.label: time
description:
The start time of the interval for which the anomaly data in the table is being aggregated.
Anomalies in the table are commonly aggregated by day, hour, or at the bucket span of the job.

children.label: source
description: The source anomaly record document, containing the full source anomaly record fields.

children.label: rowId
description: Unique identifier for the table row.

children.label: jobId
description: Identifier for the anomaly detection job.

children.label: detectorIndex
description:
A unique identifier for the detector.
This identifier is based on the order of the detectors in the analysis configuration, starting at zero.

children.label: severity
description:
Severity of the anomaly displaying the anomaly record_score, a normalized score between 0-100,
which is based on the probability of the anomalousness of this record.

children.label: entityName
description:
The entity name of the anomaly, looking first for a by_field, then over_field,
then partition_field, returning undefined if none of these fields are present.

children.label: entityValue
description: The value of the entity field.

children.label: influencers
description:
If influencers was specified in the detector configuration, this array contains influencers
that contributed to or were to blame for an anomaly.

children.label: actual
description: The actual value for the anomaly.

children.label: actualSort
description:
Property used by the table to sort anomalies by their actual value,
which is a single numeric value rather than the underlying arrays.

children.label: typical
description: The typical value for the anomaly.

children.label: typicalSort
description:
Property used by the table to sort anomalies by their typical value,
which is a single numeric value rather than the underlying arrays.

children.label: metricDescriptionSort
description:
Property used by the table to sort anomalies by the description of how the
actual value compares to the typical value.

children.label: customUrls
description:
List of custom URL drilldowns from the table row to other pages such as
Discover, Dashboard or other web pages.

children.label: isTimeSeriesViewRecord
description:
Returns true if the anomaly record represented by the table row is for a time series
which can be plotted by the ML UI in an anomaly chart.

interfaces.label: Influencer
description:
Influencers are the entities that have contributed to, or are to blame for, the anomalies.
Influencer results are available only if an influencer_field_name is specified in the job configuration.

description: The field name of the influencer.

children.label: influencer_field_values
description: The entities that influenced, contributed to, or were to blame for the anomaly.

description: A summary of an anomaly detection job.

children.label: id
description: The identifier for the anomaly detection job.

children.label: description
description: A description of the job.

children.label: groups
description: A list of job groups. A job can belong to no groups, one or many.

children.label: processed_record_count
description:
The number of input documents that have been processed by the anomaly detection job.
This value includes documents with missing fields, since they are nonetheless analyzed.

children.label: memory_status
description: The status of the mathematical models, which can take the values ok, soft_limit or hard_limit.

children.label: jobState
description: The status of the job.

children.label: datafeedIndices
description: An array of index names used by the datafeed. Wildcards are supported.

children.label: hasDatafeed
description: Flag indicating whether a datafeed exists for the job.

children.label: datafeedId
description: The identifier for the datafeed.

children.label: datafeedState
description: The status of the datafeed.

children.label: latestTimestampMs
description: The timestamp of the latest chronologically input document.

children.label: earliestTimestampMs
description: The timestamp of the earliest chronologically input document.

children.label: latestResultsTimestampMs
description: The latest of the timestamp of the latest chronologically input document or the latest bucket that was processed.

children.label: fullJob
description:
Used in older implementations of the job config, where the datafeed was placed inside the job for convenience.
This will be populated if the job's id has been passed to the /api/ml/jobs/jobs_summary endpoint.

children.label: nodeName
description: The name of the node that runs the job.

children.label: auditMessage
description: Audit message for the job.

children.label: isSingleMetricViewerJob
description: Flag indicating whether results of the job can be viewed in the Single Metric Viewer.

children.label: isNotSingleMetricViewerJobMessage
description:
For jobs which cannot be viewed in the Single Metric Viewer, a message indicating the reason why
results for the job cannot be viewed in the Single Metric Viewer.

children.label: blocked
description:
When present, it explains that a task is currently running on the job, which is stopping
any other actions from being performed on the job.

children.label: latestTimestampSortValue
description: Value of the latest timestamp for the job used for sorting.

children.label: earliestStartTimestampMs
description: The earlist of the timestamp of the earliest chronologically input document or the earliest bucket that was processed.

children.label: awaitingNodeAssignment
description: Indicates whether the job is currently awaiting assignment to a node before opening.

children.label: alertingRules
description: List of anomaly detection alerting rules configured for the job.

children.label: jobTags
description: List of tags that have been added to the job.

children.label: bucketSpanSeconds
description: The size of the interval that the analysis is aggregated into, typically between 5m and 1h.

children.label: customSettings
description: Advanced configuration option. Contains custom meta data about the job. For example, it can contain custom URL information.

interfaces.label: AnomalyRecordDoc
description:
Anomaly record document. Records contain the detailed analytical results.
They describe the anomalous activity that has been identified in the input data based on the detector configuration.

children.label: [key: string]: any
description:
Index signature to cover dynamic attributes added to the record depending on the fields being analyzed.
For example, if the job is analyzing hostname as a by field, then a field hostname is added to the result document.

children.label: job_id
description: The identifier for the anomaly detection job.

children.label: result_type
description: The type of the result document, which is 'record' for record level results.

children.label: probability
description:
The probability of the individual anomaly occurring, in the range 0 to 1.
This value can be held to a high precision of over 300 decimal places,
so the record_score is provided as a human-readable and friendly interpretation of this.

children.label: record_score
description:
A normalized score between 0-100, which is based on the probability of the anomalousness of this record.
Unlike initial_record_score, this value will be updated by a re-normalization process as new data is analyzed.

children.label: initial_record_score
description:
A normalized score between 0-100, which is based on the probability of the anomalousness of this record.
This is the initial value that was calculated at the time the bucket was processed.

children.label: bucket_span
description: The length of the bucket in seconds. This value matches the bucket_span that is specified in the job.

children.label: detector_index
description:
A unique identifier for the detector. This identifier is based on the order of the detectors
in the analysis configuration, starting at zero.

children.label: is_interim
description: If true, this is an interim result. In other words, the results are calculated based on partial input data.

children.label: timestamp
description: The start time of the bucket for which these results were calculated.

children.label: partition_field_name
description:
The field used to segment the analysis.
When you use this property, you have completely independent baselines for each value of this field.

children.label: partition_field_value
description: The value of the partition field.

children.label: function
description: The function in which the anomaly occurs, as specified in the detector configuration. For example, max.

children.label: function_description
description: The description of the function in which the anomaly occurs, as specified in the detector configuration.

children.label: field_name
description:
Certain functions require a field to operate on, for example, sum().
For those functions, this value is the name of the field to be analyzed.

children.label: typical
description: The typical value for the bucket, according to analytical modeling.

children.label: actual
description: The actual value for the bucket.

children.label: influencers
description:
If influencers was specified in the detector configuration, this array contains influencers
that contributed to or were to blame for an anomaly.

children.label: by_field_name
description:
The field used to split the data. In particular, this property is used for analyzing the splits
with respect to their own history. It is used for finding unusual values in the context of the split.

children.label: by_field_value
description: The value of the by field.

children.label: over_field_name
description:
The field used to split the data. In particular, this property is used for analyzing
the splits with respect to the history of all splits.
It is used for finding unusual values in the population of all splits.

children.label: over_field_value
description: The value of the over field.

children.label: causes
description:
For population analysis, this property contains an array of anomaly records that are the causes
for the anomaly that has been identified for the over field. If no over fields exist, this field is not present.
This sub-resource contains the most anomalous records for the over_field_name.
The causes resource contains similar elements to the record resource.
Probability and scores are not applicable to causes.
signature: { function: string; function_description: string; probability: number; actual: number[]; typical: number[]; field_name?: string | undefined; over_field_name?: string | undefined; over_field_value?: string | undefined; by_field_name?: string | undefined; by_field_value?: string | undefined; partition_field_name?: string | undefined; partition_field_value?: string | number | undefined; }[] | undefined

children.label: multi_bucket_impact
description:
An indication of how strongly an anomaly is multi bucket or single bucket.
The value is on a scale of -5.0 to +5.0 where -5.0 means the anomaly is
purely single bucket and +5.0 means the anomaly is purely multi bucket.

misc.label: AnomalyResultType
description: The type of the anomaly result, such as bucket, influencer or record.
